ce:section.ce:para:
Furthermore the carbon-based materials (e.g., CDs) are the most promising and attractive materials for electrochemical energy storage applications, as they store energy by the electrical double layer capacitance (EDLC) mechanism. Recently, CDs and CD-based composite materials have been widely used in energy storage applications, which attributes to the zero-dimensional graphitic structures with good conductivity, rapid electron transfer, electron reservoir properties, easy large scale production, and low cost (Li et al., 2015; De and Karak, 2017). However, due to the EDLC, they have poor energy density. Therefore CD-based conducting polymer nanocomposites are gaining more interest because conducting polymers have pseudocapacitive materials due to their faradaic reactions. An electrostatic self-assembled CD-reinforced polypyrrole nanowire (PPy-NW)-based nanocomposite electrode displayed a specific capacitance of 306Fg−1 at a current density of 0.5Ag−1 with a 66.8% retention of capacitance at a current density of 40Ag−1 (Jian et al., 2017b). The superior electrochemical properties of CDs/PPy-NW nanocomposite are due to the dotted-line structure with a large specific area, more active sites, and outstanding electronic conductivity. The constructed symmetric supercapacitor (Fig. 7.21
                     ) device from this nanocomposite delivered a large areal capacitance (248.5mFcm−2 at 0.2mAcm−2) and good rate capability with high cycling stability even at a high current density of 5mAcm−2 (85.2% capacitance retention after 5000cycles). Here the dotted line structure of CQDs/PPy-NW nanocomposite electrode shows a small charge transfer resistance (R
                     ct), which indicates a rapid charge/ion transfer for the nanocomposite electrode, as shown in the inset (box) in Fig. 7.21. A flexible all-solid-state supercapacitor is also fabricated from a electrochemically synthesized CDs/PPy nanocomposite electrode (Jian et al., 2017a). The CDs/PPy nanocomposite shows a combination of two types of energy storage mechanism, EDLC and pseudocapacitance. Additionally the high capacitance performance is also attributed to the CDs doped PPy for a highly porous “nanoisland” structure, which improves the redox activity of PPy and reduces the ion/electron transport internal resistance to less energy waste. The assembled supercapacitor device of CDs/PPy nanocomposite as the electrodes and separated by PVA/LiCl gel electrolyte, exhibits outstanding electrochemical performance with the areal capacitance 315mFcm−2 (corresponding to specific capacitance of 308Fg−1) at a current density of 0.2mAcm−2 and long life cycle with 85.7% retention of its initial capacitance after 2000cycles. Furthermore, it possesses a good flexibility under various mechanical bending angles from 0 to 180degree and shows similar electrochemical properties under different bending conditions. Another important conducting polymer, polyaniline-based CDs nanocomposite, is also utilized in supercapacitor electrode (Wang et al., 2017a). The flake-shaped N-doped CD/polyaniline (N-CD/PANI) nanocomposites are used as electrode materials in supercapacitors, which deliver a high specific capacitance value up to ~500Fg−1 at a current density of 1Ag−1 (Wang et al., 2017a). The enhanced electrical conductivity and electrochemical performance are achieved through the plentiful functional groups on the surfaces of the N-CDs (such as amino and carboxyl groups) are covalently grafted with the PANI chains or adsorbed via electrostatic interaction or hydrogen bonding.
